  "chunk_index": 3,
  "summary": "Mrs. Oliver meets with Poirot to report a murder that occurred the previous night at a Halloween party in Woodleigh, a residential area near London and Manchester. Mrs. Oliver explains that she had been visiting her friend, a widow named Judith Butler, and was invited to the party to provide ideas for the children's festivities.\n\nThe party featured traditional games, including an apple-biting contest and a \"dragon hunt\" involving burning raisins. Mrs. Oliver reveals that a girl named Joyce, approximately twelve or thirteen years old, was found dead in the library. Joyce was murdered by someone who pushed her head into a heavy, zinc-lined bucket filled with water and floating apples, causing her to drown. Mrs. Oliver notes that the use of a heavy bucket, rather than a plastic one, may have facilitated the drowning.\n\nDistressed by the event, Mrs. Oliver expresses a sudden, intense aversion to apples. She clarifies that while she did not know Joyce personally, she was present due to her connection to Judith Butler. Mrs. Oliver suggests the crime may be linked to her own identity, noting that a child at the party recognized her as a famous author of murder mystery books. As Poirot attempts to gather facts regarding the victim and the upcoming police interrogation, Mrs. Oliver implies that the circumstances surrounding the death are more complex than they initially appear.",
